revision.text:
{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}} {{Infobox magazine |title = Le Japon artistique |image_file = File:Le Japon artistique décembre 1889.jpg |image_size = |image_caption = December 1889 French edition |editor = [[Siegfried Bing]] |frequency = Monthly |category = [[Japanese art]] |firstdate = 1888 |finaldate = 1891 |country = |language = {{Flatlist| * English * French * German}} }} [[File:S. Bing en kimono.jpg|thumb|alt=|right|[[Siegfried Bing]] in a [[kimono]] ]] '''''Artistic Japan''''' was a magazine of [[Japanese art]], published by German-born French art dealer [[Siegfried Bing]]. It ran for thirty-six monthly issues from 1888 to 1891 in French, English, and German editions and contributed to a revival of [[Japonism]].{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=6}}
==Background== Art critics and collectors in Europe spearheaded a craze for Japanese art in the late 19th century; prominent promoters of this [[Japonism]] included [[Edmond de Goncourt]] (1822–96), [[Philippe Burty]] (1830–90), and [[Siegfried Bing]] (1838–1905).{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=7}} Burty made an attempt at a magazine devoted to Japanese art that lasted a single issue.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|pp=7–8}}
The wealthy collector and dealer Bing had placed himself at the centre of Japanese art circles in Paris;{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=8}} where he had relocated from Hamburg in Germany to take over a branch of the family business dealing in imports of [[French porcelain]].{{sfn|Hokenson|2004|pp=185–186}} In the late 1870s he opened a shop selling Japanese art objects and travelled to the Far East to study art in 1880.{{sfn|Hokenson|2004|p=186}} He developed connections with art sources in Japan and amassed what was considered one of the finest Japanese art collections in the West. He desired to spread word of Japanese aesthetics to a broad public, and used his wealth and connections to populate a new magazine to this end.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=8}}
==Publication== Bing enlisted his friend, the director of the [[Museum für Kunst und Gewerbe Hamburg]] [[Justus Brinckmann]] (1843–1915), to translate and print a German-language edition of the magazine.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=8}} The English art dealer [[Marcus Bourne Huish]] (1845–1922) handled publication of an English-language that also circulated in the United States.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=9}}
The magazine aimed to educate the public, and enjoyed high-quality printing featuring reproductions drawn from private collections.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=19}} Each issue had several colour [[tipped-in page]]s of reproductions of Japanese artwork such as paintings or [[ukiyo-e]] prints.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=12}} It featured essays on Japanese art and art history by critics such as Burty, de Goncourt, and {{illm|Louis Gonse|fr}}, drawn from Bing's wide circle of acquaintances in the art world.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|pp=12–13}} The articles examined a wide variety of Japanese arts: [[Japanese architecture|its architecture]], [[Japanese painting|painting]], [[Woodblock printing in Japan|woodblock printing]], [[Japanese pottery|pottery]], and even [[Japanese poetry|poetry]] and [[Theatre of Japan|theatre]].{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|pp=14–15}} Bing also drew attention to the high aesthetic quality of everyday objects such as combs, tea ladles, and fabrics.{{sfn|Hokenson|2004|pp=186–187}}
==Reception and legacy== Bing made effort to have ''Artistic Japan'' widely reviewed.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=9}} It received positive reviews throughout the West, as far away as Scandinavia and the US. The London-based periodical ''[[The Academy (periodical)|The Academy]]'' praised its first issue's "attractiveness". The American ''The Critic'' rated it "among the highest class of art-journal".{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=12}} The established reputations of the contributing writers to which Bing had access contributed to the magazine's quick acceptance as an authority.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=13}}
The vogue for Japanese art had reached a peak by the time the magazine appeared. French artist and collector of Japanese art [[George Auriol]] expressed hope that the magazine would rekindle an appreciation of its true aesthetic qualities in the face of its brimming commercialization.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|pp=9–10}} The ''Japan Weekly Mail'' newspaper ran regular denigrating reviews of the magazine's reproduction and writing quality{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=10}} and Bing's understanding of Japanese history and society.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=11}}
The magazine benefited Bing as a dealer, as prices for Japanese artworks rose with awareness of their value; this was one aim of Bing's, and he attracted some criticism for it.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=10}} The magazine's reproductions served as models to Western graphic designers.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=12}} Gabriel&nbsp;P. Weisberg has asserted that ''Artistic Japan'' was a major force in solidifying the valued position Japanese art was to have in the West.{{sfn|Weisberg|1986|p=19}} The aesthetic quality of the magazine itself won lasting recognition; in 1906 [[Gustav Klimt]] obtained a complete run.{{sfn|Hokenson|2004|p=187}}
